author: Jessica Schladebeck
title: Convicted sex offender arrested in shooting death of OSU student
text:
Convicted sex offender arrested in shooting death of OSU student New York Daily News 4 hrs ago Jessica Schladebeck © Provided by WKBN An initial autopsy found Reagan Tokes was shot twice. A convicted sex offender recently released from prison has been arrested in connection with the shooting death of an Ohio State University senior.
Grove City Police on Saturday announced they arrested Brian Lee Golsby, who has been charged with aggravated murder, aggravated kidnapping and aggravated robbery, WCMH reported.
Reagan Tokes, a psychology student set to graduate in the spring, was last seen leaving her job in Columbus on Wednesday night. The next day her friends reported her missing, police told the news station.
Tokes’ co-workers told detectives the 21-year-old Florida native usually had a bartender walk her to car, but did not the night she disappeared.
Police found Tokes’ naked body on Thursday near an entrance to Scioto Grove Metro park, about 12 miles away from Ohio State, according to ABC .
An initial autopsy showed the college student was shot twice, but did not uncover any other signs of trauma.
Police said evidence discovered in Tokes’ car led investigator to Golsby — he was arrested around 4 a.m. not far from where officers discovered Tokes’ car and is slated to be arraigned on Monday.
Golsby in 2010 was arrested for robbing a woman and then robbing and raping another two weeks later in an apartment complex parking lot. The victim said her toddler was in the car when she was assaulted, WCMH reported.
The 29-year-old suspect was released from prison in November.
Ohio State said in a statement that it was “deeply saddened” to learn of Tokes’ death.
“We extend our heartfelt sympathies to her family and friends,” the statement reads. “Our thoughts and prayers are with them during this extremely difficult time.”
Police have not determined a connection between Tokes and Golsby, who is a registered sex offender.
